INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (51, 1, '2010-09-25 07:19:35', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'We were deep into winter when I began what I thought would be the process of getting Jess used to the idea of me running off to yet another mountain bike weekend without her.\n\n"I''m thinking of doing the Dirt Series this summer," I said.\n\nThen I had to explain what it was, send the website etc. Then a surprising thing happened.\n\n"What if I want to go too?"\n\nWhat? Was this the person who, when I called after my first day at Mountain Bike Oregon, raving about the awesome trails, said, "I like mountain biking--just not when it''s really narrow, and there are trees really close to your bars, and drop-offs and obstacles."\n\n"Honey, you don''t like single track," I reminded her.\n\n"Well, maybe if I was a better rider, I would like it."\n\n"Um, you don''t have a bike."\n\n"If I get good, maybe I''ll get a bike."\n\nWe left it at that.\n\nBut come spring, we were back at River City Bikes (AKA our third home--the second is REI), and next thing you know, I was making room for the eighth steed to enter our now very full garage.\n\nShe requested Mondays off for all of June and July, and joined me in racing the entire Short Track race series at PIR. In just a few weeks, I watched her confidence grow and saw her casually ride over, up and down features that would have had her walking not long before.\n\nThe Dirt Series fell the weekend before the last short track race. I had heard nothing but high praise from anyone who had been through the clinic and we were both excited about learning new skills.\n\nFriday we had our usual late departure but an otherwise uneventful drive to Sisters, where we stopped for lunch and short ride on the Peterson Ridge trail to get our mountain legs.\n\nWe rode five miles up a forest service road, but the view was so lovely that I didn''t even mind. After some climbing, we turned onto the trail.\n\nIt was typical eastern Oregon single track. Firm, sandy, fun, swoopy curves and only occasional sections with obstacles, mostly little rock gardens that I powered through and Jess walked.\n\nThere was some confusion about direction. Seems a few more trails have been added since I bought my map, but we didn''t know that. It wasn''t too big a deal, except that Jess was tiring quickly, had forgotten her inhaler, and I could tell she was ready to be done. We took a fork in the road that was probably the more technical of the two, which meant more hike-a-bike for her.\n\nEventually we got past all the hard stuff, and it was a nice cruise back to the park where we started. I had to slow way down, which was frustrating, but I reminded myself that after the weekend, Jess would hopefully have the skills to ride most of what we had just ridden (and of course remembering the inhaler will help too).\n\nWe cruised into Bend, where we had found lodgings with a stranger named Dan who had listed his spare room on AirBnB. It''s not as sketchy as it sounds. He was out for the night when we arrived, but left a very thorough note and the dogs were sweet and didn''t howl at us. The extra toothbrushes and guest book were a nice touch.\n\n<strong>Saturday</strong>\n\nWe headed to Sunnyside Sports bike shop where there was the usual checking in, name tag acquisition, announcements etc. They were handing out armor to demo, and I picked up a set I had reserved in advance, and wished we''d gotten there earlier so Jess could have some too. Hers was reserved for Sunday and I just hoped she could keep herself whole without it until then. I wouldn''t normally be so nervous about it, but during our first anniversary I learned that she can be somewhat fragile when practicing high risk activities.\n\nThe most important task of the morning was to found out which groups we''d been placed in. When you register for the clinic, they send quite lengthy questionaire about your skills, abilities, what you want to learn, and (cue forshadowing), if they feel you''re on the cusp between skill groups, whether you''d rather be challenged in the harder group, or comfortable in the easier group. I picked A.\n\nJess got placed in the beginner-intermediate group, number four. Groups were rated 1-9 from easiest to hardest though the trainers seemed to want to keep that info close to the vest.\n\nWhen I got to the head of the line, the trainer checked her lists and informed me that I was in beginner group number three.\n\nTHREE? BEGINNER? SERIOUSLY?\n\nThree MBO weekends and two years of short track racing and she wanted to put me in beginner? ARE YOU $!*#*ingÂ  KIDDING ME?\n\nBut what I said was, "Wow, beginner really? Are you sure about that? I consider myself to be pretty solidly intermediate."\n\n''Yeah, it''s beginner but it''s a fit group. You''ll like it."\n\nAnd with that, it seemed, I had to be satisfied. For the moment. I spent the rest of the morning contemplating a world where I end up in a lower level mt bike skill group than Jess, who was walking over every obstacle the day before.\n\nI put it aside, and finished getting ready, which involved changing over to flat pedals for the morning clinic. The website and all the instructors were very clear on this point. They pretty much insisted that everyone use flat pedals, at least in the morning skills clinics. Jess and I had both bought some cheap ones at REI for the occasion. When I tried them for the first time, I was surprised how grippy the mountain style pedals actually are, while still allowing you to bail at will. This is key for infusing more confidence into the attendees as we try new things.\n\nIn what seemed a hectic process, we eventually all herded over to Columbia park for morning skills. Fun obstacles were scattered around the park, including teeters, skinnies, drops and ''switchbacks'' made with climbing rope.\n\nMy group started out with trainers Tracey and Pam for descending tips. We did some basic drills, learning the feel and limit of our brakes, i.e. how much pressure we can apply before they lock up. Then we learned the proper way to bail if the downhill going gets too hairy--off the back of the bike. Well, that was a revelation. Of COURSE you would want to step off in a way that lets the bike continue on while you are left standing unscathed on the trail. I saw immediately how this technique could have saved me from a silly endo on a loose switchback in Oakridge (and yet another set of knee scars....).\n\n(insert about doing drops, while watching the other group do high speed drops)\n\nAfter a couple of drills, Tracey and Pam pulled me aside.\n\n"You look really solid on your bike."\n"We don''t think you should be here."', 'Trek Dirt Series', '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2010-09-25 07:19:35', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://localhost/?p=51', 0, 'post', '', 0);
